1. Color: The Dynamic Engine
The core of Pixel UI is Dynamic Color (Monet). Instead of fixed hex codes, your app should derive its palette from the user’s wallpaper.

Implementation: Use the dynamic_color package to extract a ColorScheme.

The Roles:

Primary/On-Primary: Used for key components like FABs and active states.

Surface & Surface Variant: Use these for the background and cards. M3 has moved away from pure white backgrounds; use a slight tint of the primary color for surfaces to create a cohesive "organic" look.

Tonal Palettes: Ensure you use all 13 tonal colors. For example, use Surface Container (a new M3 role) for background depth rather than just shadows.

2. Typography: The "Google Sans" Feel
Google uses Google Sans (or its open-source sibling, Product Sans) for its brand identity. For Flutter apps targeting the Pixel look:

Font: Use Google Sans for headings and Roboto or Inter for long-form body text to improve readability.

Scale: Follow the M3 type scale strictly (Display, Headline, Title, Body, Label).

Alignment: Pixel UI often uses left-aligned headlines with generous top padding to create a sense of "airiness."

3. Elevation & Surfaces (No More Shadows)
Material 3 replaces drop shadows with Color Mappings and Surface Tinting.

Elevation Overlay: Higher elevation now means a more prominent "Surface Tint." A card at elevation 3 will look more "saturated" with the primary color than a card at elevation 1.

Shapes: Use high-radius corners. M3 components (Cards, Dialogs, Buttons) typically use a 28dp corner radius for large components and fully rounded (stadium) shapes for buttons and chips.

4. Components & Layout
To match the Pixel experience, prioritize these specific M3 components:

Navigation Bar: Use the M3 NavigationBar (not BottomNavigationBar). It uses a pill-shaped "Active Indicator" behind the icon.

Top App Bar: Use the Center-aligned or Medium/Large Top App Bar. The "Large" version shrinks into a standard bar as the user scrolls, a signature Pixel interaction.

FAB: Use the Large FAB or Extended FAB with rounded-square corners (not circles).

Segmented Buttons: Use these for switching views instead of old-style tabs where possible.

5. Motion & Transitions (The "Alive" UI)
Pixel UI feels "springy" and responsive.

Predictive Back: Ensure your design flow supports the back-gesture preview.

Shared Axis Transition: Use the animations package for page transitions. Moving from a list to a detail view should use a "Container Transform" where the card grows to fill the screen.

Easing: Use StandardEasing or EmphasizedEasing. The motion should be slow to start, fast in the middle, and very gentle at the end.

6. Progress & State Indicators
Linear/Circular Progress: Use the M3 versions which feature rounded caps (rather than flat ends).

Indeterminate Motion: The animation should be a "cycle" that feels fluid, matching the system loading indicators on a Pixel device.

Empty States: Use monochromatic, tonal illustrations that match the Outline or Secondary color roles.

7. Design Flow / UX Strategy
One-Handed Use: Move interactive elements (buttons, search bars) toward the bottom two-thirds of the screen, leaving the top for large, expressive headings.

Haptics: Integrate light haptic feedback on button presses and "heavy" haptics on long presses or successful actions.

Edge-to-Edge: Ensure your UI draws behind the navigation bar and status bar for a truly immersive look.

Recommended Tooling
Material Theme Builder: Use the Web Tool to export a theme.dart file. It will generate the light and dark schemes (including high-contrast versions) automatically.

Component Reference: Always check the M3 Component Gallery for exact padding and margin specs (e.g., standard 16dp or 24dp side margins).

