Below is a practical **Material 3 / Google Pixel** design direction you can use as the system for your app. It centers on calm surfaces, strong hierarchy, dynamic color, rounded geometry, and motion that feels native to Google’s own products. [developer.android](https://developer.android.com/develop/ui/compose/designsystems/material3)

## Overall direction

Design the app like a Pixel app first: simple layouts, lots of breathing room, soft elevation, clear typography, and very restrained branding. Use Material 3 as the full visual language, not just a component library, so colors, spacing, motion, loading states, and navigation all follow the same rules. [docs.flutter](https://docs.flutter.dev/release/breaking-changes/updated-material-3-progress-indicators)

## Color system

Build the theme around M3 color roles, not around a single brand color. The core roles are primary, secondary, and tertiary for emphasis, plus neutral and neutral-variant families for surfaces, outlines, and low-emphasis UI. [anvil](https://anvil.works/docs/how-to/creating-material-3-colour-scheme)

Use these rules:
- Primary, for the main CTA, selected states, active controls, and key highlights. [developer.android](https://developer.android.com/develop/ui/compose/designsystems/material3)
- Secondary, for less prominent accent actions and supporting UI. [developer.android](https://developer.android.com/develop/ui/compose/designsystems/material3)
- Tertiary, for contrast accents and special attention states. [developer.android](https://developer.android.com/develop/ui/compose/designsystems/material3)
- Neutral and neutral-variant, for background, cards, dividers, borders, and text hierarchy. [anvil](https://anvil.works/docs/how-to/creating-material-3-colour-scheme)
- Prefer tone-based surfaces in light and dark mode, rather than old-school shadow-heavy depth. [x](http://x.com/materialdesign/status/1639255952586326017)

For a true “Google” feel, let dynamic color drive the experience when available, and fall back to a brand seed or baseline palette when it is not. [zenn](https://zenn.dev/chmod644/articles/4b0ce6be91344b)

## Typography and tone

Use the Material 3 type scale with Roboto as the default typeface, which is the documented M3 default on Android. Keep the typography quiet and functional: large, confident titles; readable body text; minimal use of decorative styles; and consistent spacing between text groups. [m1.material](https://m1.material.io/style/typography.html)

A Pixel-like hierarchy usually means:
- Large, friendly page titles.
- Medium-weight section headers.
- Compact labels and helper text.
- No more than 3 text styles visible on one screen unless the content truly needs it.

## Shapes and surfaces

Material 3 components rely on a corner radius scale, so use rounded rectangles everywhere: cards, dialogs, sheets, chips, buttons, and input fields. Keep corners consistent across the app so the UI feels system-level, not patched together. [m3.material](https://m3.material.io/styles/shape/corner-radius-scale)

For depth, prefer tonal surfaces over dramatic shadows. Use elevation as a subtle separation cue, and keep overlays/tinting aligned with Material 3 tonal surface behavior rather than heavy shadow stacks. [composables](https://composables.com/jetpack-compose/androidx.compose.material3/material3/functions/surfaceColorAtElevation)

## Navigation flow

Use one clear primary navigation pattern and keep it consistent by device size. Bottom navigation is good for 3–5 top-level destinations, navigation rail is better on tablets and wider layouts, and drawers should not be the default unless the app is content-dense. [9to5google](https://9to5google.com/2025/05/14/material-3-expressive-navigation/)

Recommended structure:
- Mobile: bottom navigation for top-level destinations.
- Tablet / foldables: navigation rail plus contextual panes.
- Desktop/web wide layouts: rail or side navigation with persistent content regions.
- Keep destination names short and obvious.

## Components to standardize

Use Material 3 components as the default vocabulary across the app, including app bars, cards, chips, dialogs, bottom sheets, snackbars, tabs, menus, text fields, and lists. The app should feel like it belongs to the same family as Google Photos, Drive, Keep, and Pixel system surfaces: clean, purposeful, and not over-styled. [m3.material](https://m3.material.io/styles/color/roles)

Priority usage:
- Filled buttons for primary actions.
- Tonal buttons for secondary actions.
- Outlined buttons for low-emphasis actions.
- Cards and list items for content grouping.
- Sheets and dialogs for interruptions only.

## Loading and progress

Use the right progress pattern for the wait time. Flutter’s Material 3 progress indicators have been updated to match M3 specs, including refined tracks and rounded details. [docs.flutter](https://docs.flutter.dev/release/breaking-changes/updated-material-3-progress-indicators)

A good rule:
- 200 ms to 5 s: use a loading indicator style that feels immediate and lightweight. [9to5google](https://9to5google.com/2025/05/16/material-3-expressive-loading-indicator/)
- Longer uncertain waits: use linear progress or skeleton-like structure where possible.
- Only show indeterminate indicators when you cannot estimate progress.
- Avoid overusing spinners; prefer actual content loading states.

For micro-waits and refresh actions, keep animation subtle and informative rather than flashy. [9to5google](https://9to5google.com/2025/05/16/material-3-expressive-loading-indicator/)

## Motion and animation

Motion should feel fast, gentle, and useful. Material motion guidance emphasizes durations and easing that match the distance and importance of movement, instead of using one fixed animation style everywhere. [m1.material](https://m1.material.io/motion/duration-easing.html)

Use motion like this:
- Short, crisp transitions for small UI changes.
- Slightly longer motion for navigation and screen-to-screen shifts.
- Clear easing differences for entering versus leaving elements.
- Never animate just to decorate; every motion should explain state change, hierarchy, or continuity. [m1.material](https://m1.material.io/motion/duration-easing.html)

## UI behavior rules

Make the interface feel “Google” by favoring clarity over density. Keep primary actions obvious, secondary actions de-emphasized, and destructive actions visually separated and harder to trigger accidentally. [m3.material](https://m3.material.io/styles/shape)

A strong Material 3 app usually follows these principles:
- One dominant action per screen.
- Information grouped into cards or sections with consistent spacing.
- Clear empty states, loading states, error states, and success states.
- Soft, non-intrusive feedback through snackbars or inline messages.
- Persistent state indicators for selection, progress, and filters.

