Since you mentioned `dynamic_color: ^1.8.1`, the app should be built around `ThemeData(useMaterial3: true)` with dynamic color on supported devices and a clean fallback theme when dynamic color is unavailable. Use Material 3 progress widgets, tonal surfaces, and the updated navigation patterns so the app stays aligned with current Flutter Material behavior. [vibe-studio](https://vibe-studio.ai/insights/implementing-dynamic-theming-with-material-3-color-schemes-in-flutter)

## What to avoid

Avoid designs that feel “custom Android skin” rather than Google. That means:
- Avoid harsh shadows and heavy gradients.
- Avoid too many colors on one screen.
- Avoid sharp corners mixed with rounded ones.
- Avoid dense toolbars and cluttered action rows.
- Avoid animation that looks playful instead of purposeful.

## Practical design rule

If you want one simple north star: every screen should feel like it could ship inside a Google app today. That means dynamic but restrained color, rounded M3 surfaces, Roboto typography, system-like motion, and simple navigation that adapts across phone and tablet. [m3.material](https://m3.material.io/styles/typography/fonts)

